</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Event: Incoming payment</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>As an alternative, you can also use <strong>Incoming payment: complete</strong> as the event. However, if you offer <strong>purchase on invoice</strong> or <strong>cash on delivery</strong> as the payment method, then the payment would be received after the outgoing items have been booked and therefore it would no longer be possible to add an item to the shipment. This is why we recommend using <strong>Order received</strong> as the event and already adding the free item to the order at this point.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Tip: Promotional free gifts</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You should still create an item data set even if the free gift is just a promotional item that you do not actually sell. Set the item to <strong>invisible</strong> and then assign it to an invisible category, meaning a category that you do not activate for the online store.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<div class="admonitionblock tip">
<table>
<tbody><tr>
<td class="icon">
<i class="fa icon-tip" title="Tip"></i>
</td>
<td class="content">
<div class="title">Tip: Bonus item scale</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>You can set up a <strong>bonus item scale</strong> to add different items for different purchase values with the help of <strong>event procedures</strong> if you wish to go even further with give-aways. Set e.g. the filters <strong>&gt;= 100,00 EUR</strong><span class="underline">and</span><strong>&lt; 200,00 EUR</strong> for the first procedure. In the second procedure set the value of items to <strong>&gt;= 200 EUR</strong> and add another item as the free gift.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
